'''Vernice Doris Ferguson''' (June 13, 1928 - December 8, 2012) was an American nurse and healthcare executive. She was the nursing department head at the [[National Institutes of Health Clinical Center]] for several years, then served as a nurse executive with the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] for twelve years. Ferguson held faculty appointments at several American universities. She was named a Living Legend of the [[American Academy of Nursing]], was the second American named an honorary [[Fellow of the Royal College of Nursing]] in the [[United Kingdom]] and received several honorary doctorates.

==Biography==

===Early life and career===
Vernice Ferguson was born in [[Fayetteville, North Carolina]] on June 13, 1928. She grew up in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], where her father was a minister and her mother was a teacher.<ref name=NYT/> Ferguson volunteered at a hospital in high school.<ref name=Daniell>{{cite news|last=Daniell|first=Constance|title=Nurses Cares About Quality of Living|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PQMqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8igEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7208,143777&dq=vernice+ferguson&hl=en|accessdate=July 21, 2013|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal|date=February 21, 1975}}</ref>  She taught junior high school science in Baltimore before she became a nurse. She received an undergraduate degree in nursing from [[New York University]] and a masters degree from [[Columbia University Teachers College]]. She began her career as a nurse at [[Montefiore Medical Center|Montefiore Hospital]] on its NIH-funded Metabolic Neoplastic Research Unit.<ref name=NYU>{{cite web|title=Vernice D. Ferguson, NYU Nursing Alum, Head of the Veterans Affairs and National Institutes of Health Nursing Departments, Dies at the Age of 84|url=http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2012/12/10/vernice-d-ferguson-nyu-nursing-alum-head-of-the-veterans-affairs-and-national-institutes-of-health-nursing-departments-dies-at-the-age-of-84.html|publisher=[[New York University]]|accessdate=July 21, 2013}}</ref>

From 1967 to 1970, Ferguson led the nursing service at the VA hospital in [[Madison, Wisconsin]].<ref name=Daniell/> Between 1972 and 1980, Ferguson headed the nursing department at the [[National Institutes of Health Clinical Center]]. In 1980, she became the chief nursing officer for the [[Veterans Administration]], which employed around 60,000 nurses across the nation at that time. She retired in 1992.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|last=Slotnik|first=Daniel|title=Vernice D. Ferguson, Leader and Advocate of Nurses, Dies at 84|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/22/us/vernice-d-ferguson-leader-and-advocate-of-nurses-dies-at-84.html?_r=0|accessdate=July 21, 2013|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 21, 2012}}</ref> Ferguson helped to establish the [[Health Professions Scholarship Program]] during her tenure with the VA.<ref name=NYU/> Ferguson held teaching appointments at the [[University of Wisconsin at Madison]], the [[University of Illinois]], [[Georgetown University]], the [[University of Maryland]], and the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=NYU/>

She served as president of the [[American Academy of Nursing]] from 1981 to 1983<ref name=Pres>{{cite web|title=Past Academy Presidents|url=http://www.aannet.org/past-presidents|publisher=[[American Academy of Nursing]]|accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref> and as president of [[Sigma Theta Tau]] from 1985 to 1987.<ref name=IUPUI>{{cite web|title=Sigma Theta Tau International, Inc. Records, 1920-2007|url=http://www.ulib.iupui.edu/special/collections/general/mss051|work=Ruth Lilly Special Collections & Archives|publisher=[[Indiana University Purdue University Indianapolis]]|accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref>

===Awards and honors===
In 1970, Ferguson won the Mary Mahoney Award from the [[American Nurses Association]], an award that recognizes contributions to racial equality in the nursing profession.<ref name=AA>{{cite news|last=Phillips Cooke|first=Marie Murphy|title=Two Outstanding Black Women Toasted Champagne Sip|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2205&dat=19731110&id=o0xGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=deUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3384,4322407|accessdate=July 20, 2013|newspaper=[[Baltimore Afro-American]]|date=November 10, 1973}}</ref><ref name=Mahoney>{{cite web|title=Mary Mahoney Award|url=http://www.nursingworld.org/FunctionalMenuCategories/AboutANA/Honoring-Nurses/NationalAwardsProgram/NatlAwards/MaryMahoney|publisher=[[American Nurses Association]]|accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref> She was designated a Living Legend of the American Academy of Nursing in 1998. Ferguson received a New York University College of Nursing Distinguished Alumni Award in 2010. She was the first nurse to receive the FREDDIE Lifetime Achievement Award, which recognizes excellence in medical media production.<ref name=RWJF>{{cite web|title=Vernice Ferguson Becomes First Nurse to Win FREDDIE|url=http://www.rwjf.org/en/about-rwjf/newsroom/newsroom-content/2008/12/vernice-ferguson-becomes-first-nurse-to-win-freddie.html|publisher=[[Robert Wood Johnson Foundation]]|accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref> Ferguson was the second American named an honorary [[Fellow of the Royal College of Nursing]] in the United Kingdom.<ref name=NYU/>

===Later life and legacy===
In 1992, Ferguson retired from the VA and was named a senior fellow with the nursing program at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. She was 84 years old when she died on December 8, 2012 in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=NYT/> A memorial scholarship is awarded in her honor by the Nurses Organization of Veterans Affairs.<ref name=Memorial>{{cite web|title=Vernice Ferguson Memorial Scholarship|url=http://www.vanurse.org/?query=Vernice+Ferguson+Memorial+Scholarship|publisher=Nurses Organization of Veterans Affairs|accessdate=July 21, 2013}}</ref>

